<tr>
<td colspan="2" style="text-align: center; border-bottom: 1px solid #aaa;"></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Contract bridge</b>, usually known simply as <b>bridge</b>, is a <a href="/wiki/Trick-taking_game" title="Trick-taking game">trick-taking</a> <a href="/wiki/Card_game" title="Card game">card game</a> of <a href="/wiki/Game_of_skill" title="Game of skill">skill</a> and <a href="/wiki/Game_of_chance" title="Game of chance">chance</a> (the relative proportions depending on the variant played). It is played by four players who form two partnerships; the partners sit opposite each other at a table. The game consists of the auction (often called bidding) and play, after which the hand is scored.</p>
<p>The bidding ends with a <i>contract</i>, which is a declaration by one partnership that their side will take at least a stated number of tricks, with a specified <a href="/wiki/Suit_(cards)" title="Suit (cards)">suit</a> as <a href="/wiki/Trump_(cards)" title="Trump (cards)" class="mw-redirect">trump</a> or without trumps. The rules of play are similar to other trick-taking games, with addition of the feature that one player's hand is displayed face up on the table as the "dummy".</p>
<p>Bridge can be played in <a href="/wiki/Tournaments" title="Tournaments" class="mw-redirect">tournaments</a>, where two or more tables play the same deals of cards and the results are compared; this form is called <a href="/wiki/Duplicate_bridge" title="Duplicate bridge">duplicate bridge</a>. Competitions in duplicate bridge range from small clubs with only a few tables, to the <a href="/wiki/Bermuda_Bowl" title="Bermuda Bowl">World Championships</a> and <a href="/wiki/World_Bridge_Olympiad" title="World Bridge Olympiad" class="mw-redirect">Olympiads</a> where often hundreds of tables play the same hands.</p>
